    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-12-27T06:26:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-12-27T06:26:00-05:00" n="569"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d569">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">Paris Peace Conf. 871.48/2: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">Commission to Negotiate Peace</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-12-27T06:26:00-05:00"
                            >December 27, 1918—6:26 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received December 28—9 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>9. Department has received following telegram from American Legation Bucharest
                        <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“20. December 20th. In addition to telegrams 18 and 19<note n="47"
                                xml:id="d569fn47">Neither printed.</note> which I have today sent
                            from Her Majesty the Queen of Roumania to Mr. Davison<note n="48"
                                xml:id="d569fn48">Henry P. Davison, chairman of the War Council of
                                the American Red Cross.</note> and Mr. Anderson<note n="49"
                                xml:id="d569fn49">Henry W. Anderson, American Red Cross commissioner
                                in charge of relief work in the Balkan States.</note> through the
                            Department and also in addition to the telegram sent by the Allied
                            Ministers here on the 18th,<note n="50" xml:id="d569fn50">Not
                                printed.</note> I beg to again plead for Roumania where, unless
                            immediate help is received, hunger will most certainly press within 30
                            days. The most pressing need is for wheat after which comes linen, ready
                            made clothing, boots, and cloth. If any Commission is sent by the
                            American Red Cross it should be sent on the same steamer as the
                            supplies.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>Please communicate to Hoover.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Polk</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
